When using a static site on bitbucket (username.bitbucket.org) and you have some html code within a javascript string, then bitbucket will also inject javascript (I guess rum.js) there.

For example it will be injected in _htmlVariableStart_.

{code}
#!html

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
    <head>
        <title>Test Page</title>
        <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.11.2.min.js"></script>
        <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-migrate-1.2.1.min.js"></script>
        <script type="text/javascript">
            var htmlVariableStart = &#x27;<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8"></head><body>&#x27;;
            var htmlVariableEnd = &#x27;</body></html>&#x27;;

            $(document).ready(function() {
                var newWindow = window.open();
                newWindow.document.write(htmlVariableStart + &#x27;It doesn\&#x27;t work&#x27; + htmlVariableEnd);
            });
        </script>
    </head>
    <body>
    </body>
</html>
{code}

Sometimes attempting to create a pull request from the web clients results in an error, but the client makes no indication of that fact:

POST to: https://bitbucket.org/hireanesquire/hae/pull-request/new

{"errors": {"source": ["No such choice 1070-strip-cc-and-bank-fe (117207674233)"]}, "error": "An error occurred saving this pull request. Please check the required fields and try again"}

This type of command:

{code}
#!text
curl --user &#x27;myuser:mypassword&#x27; --data &#x27;key=ssh-rsa+XXXXMYSSHKEYXXXX+bitbucket&label=mylabel&#x27; https://bitbucket.org/api/1.0/users/amosoft/ssh-keys
{code}

Returns :

{code}
#!text
This API has been deprecated and is not available through OAuth2 or JWT
{code}

Not sure if this has to do with the type of group created or the size of team, but here is how to reproduce:

* Create a repository on a 50 user team
* Create a user group with no level of access and add a user into the group
* Add this group to the newly created repository under &#x27;Access management&#x27;
* Fork the repository, be sure to check &#x27;Inherit permissions / groups&#x27;
* Check &#x27;Access management&#x27; of the child: The group from the parent is not inherited

With my name and password, this works:

{code:bash}
curl -X POST -v -u username:password -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/pjump/new-repository4 \
  -d &#x27;{"scm": "git", "is_private": "true", "fork_policy": "no_public_forks" }&#x27;
{code}

So does

{code:bash}
  curlicue -- --fail --silent -X DELETE "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/pjump/new-repository4" 
{code}

which would imply my authorization is correct (the second example assumes my consumer_key and consumer secret are saved in {{~/.curlicue/api.bitbucket.org}} -- curlicue then does the 2-legged oauth signing).

However, doing the same thing with POST gives me an authentication failure ( HTTP/1.1 401 UNAUTHORIZED).

{code:bash}
curlicue -- -X POST -v -H "Content-Type: application/json"  https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/pjump/new-repository1  -d &#x27;{"scm": "git", "is_private": "true", "fork_policy": "no_public_forks" }&#x27;
{code}

I think this is a bug in the bitbucket API.
